The comprehensive crisis in Lebanon
Beirut — Looking back, financial crises typically seem to have precursors; yet they seldom provide clear signposts for how history will unfold.
The situation in Lebanon is similarly characterized by a foreseeable crisis that has plunged the country into high instability.
Since the end of Lebanon's long civil war (1975-1990), its economy and political system have been supported by external borrowing, which inevitably led to a sustained rise in public debt.
At some point, the inflow of external capital had to stop. This point came toward the end of 2019, and a series of negative shocks ensued.
This sudden halt of capital has brought severe triple crises to this country.
The first issue is the balance of payments.
Lebanon's current-account deficit amounts to as much as 25% of GDP, with its export base too small to cover even the necessary imports.
The second issue is fiscal affairs.
The public debt of Lebanon now totals over 150% of its gross domestic product.
Government revenue is collapsing under the weight of the economic downturn, with a budget deficit that is already substantial, accounting for 10% of GDP in 2019 and is still expanding rapidly.
The most important thing is that Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
Main banks, which are the primary recipients of foreign capital inflows, have made substantial investments in Lebanese sovereign debt (accounting on average for 50% of their investment portfolios) and are now essentially insolvent.
These crises have together plunged Lebanon's economy into a abyss.
Companies desperate for loans and imports have already begun laying off workers or shutting down entirely.
An economic recession could lead to Lebanon's Great Depression.
The main source of capital supporting Lebanon's fragile political and economic system is not oil, but expatriates who invest there attracted by high interest rates and the fixed exchange rate tied to the dollar.
And it is not surprising, then, that signs of a “Dutch disease” abound: deposits have grown to over 400% of GDP, creating a wealth effect that has pushed down the saving rate to an unlikely 3% of GDP.
The level of inequality is very high and is still rising.
From 2000 to 2015, the real (inflation-adjusted) exchange rate appreciated by about 50%, significantly weakening the competitiveness of tradable industries.
Due to the lack of exportable goods and services, Lebanon has been losing educated young people.
But more importantly, large-scale capital inflows allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their position through sponsorship rather than merit.
These elites extracted wealth from both public and private sectors, establishing a bloated clique of rulers.
Though this ensured political stability in what had been a chaotic region, it failed to meet basic needs.
Even the power supply is intermittent and unreliable, while broader macroeconomic challenges remain entirely unresolved.
The financial crisis sparked a political uprising.
A grassroots revolutionary movement has taken to the streets to oppose sectarianism and demand an end to corruption.
Nevertheless, so far, the country’s regime has responded to Lebanon’s economic problems in a manner that is overwhelmingly biased toward the elites, suggesting that this crisis may ultimately be resolved – with the support of the poor and middle classes – in a way that further entrenches sectarian politics.
For example, the country refuses to introduce capital controls, allowing each bank’s major shareholders – which include governing politicians – to decide how much cash can be withdrawn quantitatively.
In fact, this allows elites to transfer capital abroad, while ordinary citizens struggle to access their deposits.
In addition, the central bank lowered deposit rates but has not yet reduced public debt rates, thereby increasing bank profits.
Despite continuous declines in international reserves, Lebanon continued to repay its major external debts to domestic banks.
There are signs that it may start selling state assets at fire-sale prices to elite-connected entities.
At the same time, the official exchange rate remained unchanged, and the elites were allowed to obtain dollars at a low official rate, while ordinary citizens faced the reality of a rapidly depreciating market exchange rate. The current market exchange rate is trading at a 40% discount.
When the country starts printing lira to pay public sector salaries, the depreciation will accelerate.
In fact, the central bank is already paying interest on dollar deposits in lira (with dollar deposits comprising over 80% of total deposits), thereby creating conditions for inflation to erode public debt.
As the cost of debt reduction is shifted to depositors through "liraization" with shareholding by depositors, banks' equity can be largely spared.
If this were to become reality, Lebanon's middle class would significantly shrink due to a reduction in real wages and pensions, as well as the depletion of savings.
The migration process of educated young people will be accelerated, and even the economic interests of migrant communities — upon which this system depends — will be harmed.
If the sectarian system is to survive under these conditions, it will rule over a system of impoverished people, who can be controlled by increasingly cheaper shelters.
Ultimately, Lebanon will find itself in a similar situation to Venezuela.
In contrast, the establishment of the new republic by the revolutionaries will take a completely different approach.
The revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, not abandon it.
They believe that its performance falls far short of its potential, and that performance excellence, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, favoritism, and inequality.
They hope to establish vibrant high-tech industries, make agriculture more sustainable environmentally, position the country as a cultural powerhouse, and foster greater synergies with immigrant communities.
To achieve these goals, the reform movement hopes to seek an orderly reduction in public debt, which would be underwritten by bank equity, and to compulsorily reduce the deposits of savers who account for more than 1% of total deposits by over 50%.
They support moderate currency depreciation and a comprehensive improvement in the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will seek a deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the eradication of corrupt practices, and increasing expenditure on social programs and infrastructure.
With the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable recession will be mitigated.
The infighting now surrounding the composition of Lebanon's next cabinet is part of a larger struggle as the country seeks new political solutions.
The financial crisis poses a mortal threat to this country; but it also represents an opportunity for political change.
The future of Lebanon remains unresolved.
